  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the most misunderstood obligations in Queensland real estate is the duty to disclose material facts. Many sellers assume that if a buyer does not ask about something, they are not required to mention it. That assumption is incorrect and it can be expensive. Queensland law imposes a positive duty on sellers to disclose facts that would influence a reasonable buyer's decision to buy the property or the price they would pay for it. That duty exists whether or not the buyer asks directly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What makes a fact "material"</h2>
      <p>A material fact is any fact that would, if known to a buyer, influence their decision to proceed with the purchase or change the price they would offer. The test is objective: it is not what the seller thinks is significant, but what a reasonable buyer in that market would consider significant. Courts and tribunals in Queensland have consistently applied a broad interpretation of this standard.</p>

      <p>The scope of what counts as material is wider than most sellers expect. It includes physical defects in the property, but it also includes neighbourhood conditions, past events, legal encumbrances, and anything that affects the property's amenity or value. If you are uncertain whether a particular fact is material, the safer assumption is that it is. The cost of disclosing something that turns out not to be material is minimal. The cost of failing to disclose something that is material can be substantial.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Examples of facts sellers must disclose</h2>
      <p>Structural defects that are known to the seller must be disclosed. This includes significant cracks, foundation movement, roof defects, and water ingress. It does not require you to engage a building inspector before selling (though that can be useful), but it does require you to disclose what you know. A seller who is aware of a significant structural issue and does not disclose it is not protected by the fact that they chose not to confirm it with a report.</p>

      <p>Flooding history is a disclosure obligation that has become particularly significant in Queensland following flood events in recent years. If the property has been inundated, that is a material fact. Buyers and their solicitors routinely search flood records, but a seller who discloses flooding history proactively, and provides documentation of any remediation work, is in a stronger position than one who leaves buyers to discover it through their own searches.</p>

      <p>Easements, covenants, and encumbrances affecting the property are disclosed through the contract documents and title searches, but sellers should be aware that easements affecting access, view corridors, or drainage can influence buyer decisions. If there is something unusual about the property's legal title or encumbrances beyond standard utility easements, it is worth raising with your solicitor before listing.</p>

      <p>Neighbourhood nuisances are a category that frequently catches sellers out. Known and ongoing noise from a nearby industrial facility, a consistently noisy neighbour, a regularly used public space immediately adjacent to the property, or any other neighbourhood condition that materially affects the amenity of the property is a disclosure obligation if the seller is aware of it. "I didn't think to mention it" is not a defence if the fact is material and the seller knew about it.</p>

      <p>Legal disputes affecting the property must also be disclosed. This includes disputes with neighbours over boundaries or access, ongoing body corporate disputes in a strata or community title scheme, and any litigation affecting the title or use of the property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The consequences of non-disclosure</h2>
      <p>A buyer who discovers after exchange that a material fact was not disclosed has a number of potential remedies under Queensland law. They may be entitled to rescind the contract, returning the property to the seller and recovering their deposit. They may have a claim for damages equivalent to the difference between the price paid and the value of the property with the undisclosed issue factored in. In serious cases, there may be grounds for claims of fraudulent or misleading conduct.</p>

      <p>Beyond the legal exposure to the seller directly, the agent involved in the sale can face professional conduct complaints to the Real Estate Institute or the Office of Fair Trading if they were aware of or should have been aware of a material fact and did not ensure it was disclosed. A competent agent will ask you directly about known issues with the property before the agency agreement is signed, and the answers you give to those questions matter.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The limits of "I didn't know"</h2>
      <p>Sellers sometimes assume that if they genuinely did not know about a defect or issue, they cannot be liable for non-disclosure. Knowledge is relevant, but the protection is narrower than it might appear. Wilful blindness, deliberately choosing not to investigate a potential issue so that you can claim ignorance, does not provide a defence in the same way that genuine lack of knowledge does. A seller who notices water staining on a ceiling, suspects roof damage, and chooses not to investigate before selling is in a different position from a seller who simply never saw the staining.</p>

      <p>Practically, this means that if you have any reason to suspect a material defect, investigating it before listing is better than proceeding without confirmation. A pre-sale building inspection, conducted and disclosed to buyers upfront, typically produces better outcomes for sellers than leaving buyers to discover issues in their own due diligence. Known issues presented transparently, ideally with quotes for repair, allow buyers to price the issue accurately. Unknown issues discovered by buyers tend to result in more aggressive discounting or contract rescission.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to work through disclosure before you list</h2>
      <p>The most effective time to address disclosure obligations is before you sign the agency agreement, not during the campaign or at contract. Your solicitor is the right person to work through this with you. They can review what you know about the property, identify which facts are likely to be material, and advise on how to document and disclose them appropriately in the contract of sale.</p>

      <p>Your agent should also be asking you directly about known issues as part of the listing process. If they are not asking, that is a problem. A competent agent wants to know what they are selling so they can position it honestly and ensure the campaign reaches buyers who are appropriate for the property. An agent who avoids difficult conversations about disclosure is not protecting you; they are creating risk for both of you.</p>

      <p>Getting disclosure right is not complicated, but it requires honesty and a willingness to have the conversation before the campaign launches. The sellers who encounter problems are generally those who hoped an issue would not come up, rather than those who addressed it directly from the outset.</p>

